<article>

  <p>
    Sit down intending to stay with the breath, and watch what the mind actually does.
    It plans the afternoon. It rehearses a conversation. It congratulates itself for
    sitting. It wonders whether this is working. For long stretches, attention is not
    on the object at all — it is inside a story that has not noticed itself as a story.
    That is ordinary. It is also the condition the path refuses to treat as destiny.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">Jhāna</span>
    is the Pali name for a mind that has gathered far enough to rest — not as a mood,
    and not as a trophy. In the canon it is the explicit definition of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammā-samādhi" data-en="right unification">sammā-samādhi</span>,
    the eighth factor of the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>.
    On this site it sits in Deepening: once a
    <a href="/concepts/how-to-sit/">starting sit</a>
    and the
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/">hindrances</a>
    are underway — samādhi training among the three, not a prize that waits until
    insight has rearranged experience. The texts describe it in the same
    standardised language again and again. What they do not do is present it as
    the end of the work.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Neither Fireworks nor Ordinary Focus</h2>

  <p>
    Two popular pictures of absorption pull in opposite directions, and both miss the
    texts. One treats
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhāna</span>
    as an exotic attainment reserved for monastics on long retreat — luminous,
    rare, slightly unreal. The other treats it as nothing more than “paying attention,”
    as if any stretch of undistracted sitting already counted. Neither characterisation
    is quite right.
  </p>

  <p>
    The first picture turns stillness into mystique. The second dissolves the teaching
    into a slogan. What the canon describes is more specific: a unified state that
    arises when sensual preoccupation and unwholesome agitation have thinned enough for
    the mind to settle on its object without constant recruitment elsewhere. It has
    named factors. It deepens by simplification. It is trainable — and it is not
    trivial.
  </p>

  <p>
    There is a third confusion worth naming early. Because the early absorptions can
    feel intensely pleasant, practice begins to hunt the pleasure. Rapture becomes the
    point. Ease becomes a collectible. The mind that was supposed to grow still starts
    grasping at stillness the way it once grasped at anything else. That is still
    craving — only better dressed.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Stillness Is For</h2>

  <p>
    In the path’s own grammar,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhāna</span>
    is not liberation. It is the condition in which
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paññā" data-en="wisdom">paññā</span>
    can do its work without constant distortion. A stirred mind can still recite the
    teachings. It cannot reflect them. The Buddha’s water similes for the
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrance">nīvaraṇas</span></a>
    make the point without romance: dye, heat, weeds, wind, mud. When the water settles,
    what was always there becomes visible.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why right unification sits where it does on the path — after view,
    intention, speech, action, livelihood, effort, and mindfulness have already begun
    to reshape the conditions of attention. Absorption does not float free of the rest
    of the training. A quieter mind without ethical restraint and wise orientation
    easily becomes a private shelter. The
    <a href="/concepts/three-trainings/">three trainings</a>
    page maps that interdependence; this page stays with what the absorptions themselves
    are.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course a stretch of relief after a hindrance loosens can feel like arrival. It
    usually is not.
    <a href="/concepts/when-a-hindrance-dissolves/">Absence of an obstruction</a>
    is not yet absorption.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">Jhāna</span>
    has its own texture and depth. Confusing the first clear patch with the thing the
    path names as
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sammā-samādhi" data-en="right unification">sammā-samādhi</span>
    hardens into pride when the quiet holds — and into doubt when the next difficult
    sit arrives.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How the Mind Simplifies</h2>

  <p>
    The four
    <span class="pali" data-pali="rūpa" data-en="form">rūpa</span>-jhānas
    — form absorptions — are best read as one movement: progressive dropping of what
    is still coarse. The mind does not collect more experiences. It needs less activity
    to remain gathered. Worth holding lightly: formulas are maps, not scoreboards. The
    point is the direction of refinement, not a certificate for having “got” a level.
  </p>

  <h3>First jhāna — applied attention and ease</h3>

  <p>
    The standard formula begins with withdrawal from sensual pleasures and unwholesome
    states. What characterises the first absorption are five factors:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vitakka" data-en="applied thought">vitakka</span>
    — the placing of attention on the object;
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vicāra" data-en="sustained thought">vicāra</span>
    — the sustained turning that keeps contact;
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">pīti</span>
    — energetic rapture or uplift, sometimes quite physical;
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sukha" data-en="pleasure / ease">sukha</span>
    — quieter pleasure and ease;
    and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="ekaggatā" data-en="one-pointedness">ekaggatā</span>
    — unification, the mind gathered rather than scattered.
  </p>

  <p>
    In everyday cognition,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vitakka" data-en="applied thought">vitakka</span>
    and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vicāra" data-en="sustained thought">vicāra</span>
    look like discursive thinking. In the first jhāna they become more refined: the mind
    still applies itself to the object, but without the running commentary that owns
    ordinary hours.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">Pīti</span>
    can arrive as goosebumps, tingling, a flooding sense in the body — a sign of
    deepening stillness, not a destination. The tradition even grades it; the grading
    is diagnostic, not a ladder for bragging.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Buddha’s simile is bath powder kneaded with water until the whole mass is
    saturated and nothing falls outside. The stillness is thorough, not partial.
  </p>

  <h3>Second jhāna — without the discursive push</h3>

  <p>
    In the second jhāna,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vitakka" data-en="applied thought">vitakka</span>
    and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vicāra" data-en="sustained thought">vicāra</span>
    cease. What remains is simpler: inner confidence, stillness, a mind no longer
    pushing toward the object but present with it.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">Pīti</span>
    and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sukha" data-en="pleasure / ease">sukha</span>
    continue;
    <span class="pali" data-pali="ekaggatā" data-en="one-pointedness">ekaggatā</span>
    deepens. The simile is a lake fed from within by cool springs — no external
    agitation, a coolness that suffuses the whole.
  </p>

  <h3>Third jhāna — ease without the charge</h3>

  <p>
    In the third,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">pīti</span>
    fades. The energetic charge drops. What remains is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sukha" data-en="ease">sukha</span>
    with
    <span class="pali" data-pali="upekkhā" data-en="equanimity">upekkhā</span>
    beginning to stand forward, and
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    clear and undistracted. The noble ones, the canon says, declare this state: one who
    has equanimity and is mindful dwells in ease. The simile is a lotus grown in water,
    suffused by that water, not touching the mud.
  </p>

  <h3>Fourth jhāna — equanimity and bare unification</h3>

  <p>
    In the fourth,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sukha" data-en="pleasure / ease">sukha</span>
    drops away — along with its contrast,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>.
    What remains is pure
    <span class="pali" data-pali="upekkhā" data-en="equanimity">upekkhā</span>
    with
    <span class="pali" data-pali="ekaggatā" data-en="one-pointedness">ekaggatā</span>:
    a mind still, aware, balanced. The breath, the texts note, has become very subtle.
    The simile is a person wrapped head to foot in a white cloth, every part covered.
    The stillness is total — and still conditioned.
  </p>

  <p>
    The fourth jhāna is often described as a platform: formless absorptions,
    extraordinary knowledges, and the penetrating clarity that liberation requires can
    arise from a mind this settled. Platform is the right word. Launching ground is not
    the same as arrival.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Stillness Without Seeing Is Not Release</h2>

  <p>
    A long debate in the tradition asks how deep absorption must be before insight can
    liberate — calm first, or clear seeing without full jhāna. The question is genuine.
    Nothing here pretends to settle the commentarial dispute. What the suttas make hard
    to miss is simpler: liberation does not come from absorption alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    A practitioner can enter and leave all four
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhānas</span>
    and remain unawakened if wisdom has not been applied to what appears there. Stillness
    provides conditions.
    <span class="pali" data-pali="paññā" data-en="wisdom">Paññā</span>
    does the seeing. And the support runs both ways: a mind that is deeply still can see
    more clearly; seeing more clearly deepens stillness. The path spirals.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unwholesome states, one
      enters and dwells in the first jhāna — accompanied by applied and sustained
      thought, with rapture and pleasure born of seclusion. One drenches, saturates,
      fills, and pervades the body with that rapture and pleasure, so that there is
      no part of the whole body unpervaded.
    </p>
    <cite>— DN 2 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The image is saturation and clarity, not escape. Pleasure born of seclusion is real.
    It is also not the unconditioned. Treating the pleasant unification as
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation / extinguishing">nibbāna</span>
    is one of the oldest category errors in contemplative life.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Further Still — Still Conditioned</h2>

  <p>
    Beyond the four form absorptions, the tradition describes four formless ones: the
    base of infinite space, infinite consciousness, nothingness, and
    neither-perception-nor-non-perception. These refine
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span>
    further — even the subtle sense of a physical body as object released.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the Buddha’s biography they appear as states learned from pre-awakening teachers
    and then left behind — not because they are worthless, but because even the most
    refined absorption is still
    <span class="pali" data-pali="saṅkhāra" data-en="formations">conditioned</span>,
    still
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanent">impermanent</span>,
    and unable by itself to uproot
    <span class="pali" data-pali="avijjā" data-en="ignorance">avijjā</span>.
    Peace without wisdom is peace without release. The water can become extraordinarily
    still. Seeing what the stillness is — and what it is not — remains the work.
  </p>

</article>
